In article <199407071833.NAA11644@indial1.io.com>, ritter@io.com (Terry
Ritter) writes:

> It is certainly true that if one changes the DES key for every data
> block one has a much stronger cipher.  But "stands forever"?

Well "forever" is a little strong. Nonetheless, DES will die because other
mechanism are more demonstrable and easier to implement in software long
before it dies because the cost of a brute force attack is too low.

